[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] By default, pgvector performs exact nearest neighbor search, which provides perfect recall.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] You can add an index to use approximate nearest neighbor search, which trades some recall for speed.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] Unlike typical indexes, you will see different results for queries after adding an approximate index.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] An HNSW index creates a multilayer graph.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] It has better query performance than IVFFlat (in terms of speed-recall tradeoff), but has slower build times and uses more memory.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] Also, an index can be created without any data in the table since there isn’t a training step like IVFFlat.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] Add an index for each distance function you want to use.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] A higher value of `ef_construction` provides better recall at the cost of index build time / insert speed.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] A higher value provides better recall at the cost of speed.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] An IVFFlat index divides vectors into lists, and then searches a subset of those lists that are closest to the query vector.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] It has faster build times and uses less memory than HNSW, but has lower query performance (in terms of speed-recall tradeoff).
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] There are a few ways to index nearest neighbor queries with a `WHERE` clause.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] A good place to start is creating an index on the filter column.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] This can provide fast, exact nearest neighbor search in many cases.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] Postgres has a number of index types for this: B-tree (default), hash, GiST, SP-GiST, GIN, and BRIN.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] For multiple columns, consider a multicolumn index.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] Exact indexes work well for conditions that match a low percentage of rows.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] Otherwise, approximate indexes can work better.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] With approximate indexes, filtering is applied *after* the index is scanned.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] If a condition matches 10% of rows, with HNSW and the default `hnsw.ef_search` of 40, only 4 rows will match on average.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] For more rows, enable iterative index scans, which will automatically scan more of the index when needed.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] If filtering by only a few distinct values, consider partial indexing.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] If filtering by many different values, consider partitioning.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] With approximate indexes, queries with filtering can return less results since filtering is applied *after* the index is scanned.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] Starting with 0.8.0, you can enable iterative index scans, which will automatically scan more of the index until enough results are found (or it reaches `hnsw.max_scan_tuples` or `ivfflat.max_probes`).
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] Iterative scans can use strict or relaxed ordering.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] Since scanning a large portion of an approximate index is expensive, there are options to control when a scan ends.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] Use together with Postgres full-text search for hybrid search.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] You can use Reciprocal Rank Fusion or a cross-encoder to combine results.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] Use a tool like PgTune to set initial values for Postgres server parameters.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] For instance, `shared_buffers` should typically be 25% of the server’s memory.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] Be sure to restart Postgres for changes to take effect.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] Use the `halfvec` type instead of `vector` for a smaller working set.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] Use `COPY` for bulk loading data (example).
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] Add any indexes *after* loading the initial data for best performance.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] See index build time for HNSW and IVFFlat.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] Use binary quantization for smaller indexes and faster build times at scale.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] In production environments, create indexes concurrently to avoid blocking writes.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] Use `EXPLAIN (ANALYZE, BUFFERS)` to debug performance.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] To speed up queries without an index, increase `max_parallel_workers_per_gather`.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] If vectors are normalized to length 1 (like OpenAI embeddings), use inner product for best performance.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] Use binary quantization with re-ranking to keep indexes in-memory at scale.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] To speed up queries with an IVFFlat index, increase the number of inverted lists (at the expense of recall).
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] Vacuuming can take a while for HNSW indexes.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] Scale vertically by increasing memory, CPU, and storage on a single instance.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] Use existing tools to tune parameters and monitor performance.
