[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] Each vector takes `4 * dimensions + 8` bytes of storage.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] Each element is a single-precision floating-point number (like the `real` type in Postgres), and all elements must be finite (no `NaN`, `Infinity` or `-Infinity`).
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] Vectors can have up to 16,000 dimensions.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] Each half vector takes `2 * dimensions + 8` bytes of storage.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] Each element is a half-precision floating-point number, and all elements must be finite (no `NaN`, `Infinity` or `-Infinity`).
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] Half vectors can have up to 16,000 dimensions.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] Each bit vector takes `dimensions / 8 + 8` bytes of storage.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] Each sparse vector takes `8 * non-zero elements + 16` bytes of storage.
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] Each element is a single-precision floating-point number, and all elements must be finite (no `NaN`, `Infinity` or `-Infinity`).
[src:pgvector/blob-readme-md] Sparse vectors can have up to 16,000 non-zero elements.
